d. MDRRMC to evaluate the feasibility of the planned PPAs especially those held under Continuing Appropriations, and identify projects which will no longer be implemented for possible reversion and reprogramming;
e. Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant present to the MDRRMC the savings from completed projects in CY 2022 and previous years for appropriation to other disaster preparedness and mitigation PPAs of the Municipality in the succeeding year; and
f. MDRRMO to submit monthly reports on the utilization of the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund (LDRRMF) for the succeeding periods in compliance with Section 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:

a. Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor the funds under the TF-LDRRMF for any unutilized amount that will pass the five-year retention period and immediately transfer the unexpended balance in CY 2017 after determining the same to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund which shall be made available for other social services after subsequent enactment by the local sanggunian in compliance with Section 5.1.13 of COA Circular No. 2012-002;

b. Municipal Accountant to prepare separate Subsidiary Ledger per year of transfer to the STF to ensure the proper monitoring of the five-year retention period;

c. Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjusting entries in relation to the error in the amount transferred to the TL-DRRMF account;

d. MDRRMC to evaluate the feasibility of planned PPAs, especially those held under Continuing Appropriations, and identify projects which will no longer be implemented for possible reversion and reprogramming to other disaster-related PPAs;

e. Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant present to the MDRRMC the savings from completed projects in CY 2022 and previous years for appropriation to other disaster preparedness and mitigation PPAs of the Municipality in the succeeding year; and

f. MDRRMO to submit to the Audit Team the monthly report on the utilization of the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund (LDRRMF) for the succeeding periods in compliance with Section 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive thru the Local Development Council exert efforts to fully attain the purpose and intent in establishing the 20% Development Fund at the soonest possible time through the following:
maximize appropriations of the 20% development fund released allotment;
coordinate with the National Agencies, Barangay or Province which may have projects for implementation that might coincide with the planned project of the Municipality;
carefully plot the timing of implementation with the availability of IRA;
have proper coordination among the project beneficiaries and the officials involved in planning, execution and monitoring of the projects
We also recommended that Management cause the immediate
implementation of the projects that had been allocated funds in order to fully attain the purpose and intent for establishing the fund at the soonest possible time, thereby, maximizing the real value of the money on hand.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
properly ensure that cash advances are liquidated as soon as the purpose for which it was given has been served, or within 30 days after return to permanent official station in case of local travel;
immediately issue demand letters enjoining the concerned officials with unliquidated cash advance;
allow only those duly appointed or designated disbursing officers perform disbursing functions;
cause the withholding of salary of the Accountable Officers (AOs) who failed to settle/liquidate their cash advances despite the issuance of demand letters in accordance with Section 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002; and
exercise utmost diligence in monitoring liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that the:
Management appropriate funds for the improvement/rehabilitation of electric wiring at the sanitary landfill to increase the power supply thereat so as to support the needs of the SWM equipment and also for the repair of the composting drum and dump truck;
establishment of Materials Recovery Facility be required in the barangays not only as a sorting and storage prior to collection but for recycling and composting;
include incentive based programs on its 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan as prescribed under RA 9003;
implement separate collection schedule for each type of waste, as practicable; and
dispose plastic wastes through other means possible so as not to accumulate them and cause undesirable effects in the landfill.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor ensure that:
the Management appropriate at least 5% of total appropriations for GAD as required under pertinent regulations;
the TWG conduct proper survey and study as guided by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2013-01 to determine gender issues surfacing in the locality and perform gender mainstreaming of the activities of the Municipality and its programs for the barangays;
the TWG prepare a GAD Plan based on established gender issues, specify the cause and objective and the funds allocated to finance each and every activity and submit the same to DILG for review and approval;
a GAD Code be formulated and passed to set up and maintain the GAD database that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation; and
ensure proper implementation of GAD related projects incorporated in the DILG approved GAD Plan and Budget.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Mayor require the members of the Bids and Awards Committee to submit justification on the recommendation made to award procurement of contracts to the bidders/suppliers with unknown qualification and fake eligibility requirements
Instruct the members of the Bids and Awards Committee to check, verify and validate all the tax clearance certificates submitted by the contractors awarded contracts by the Municipal Government and submit a report on the results thereon;
Impose on the contractors the penalties and administrative sanctions on the submission of false documents as required of Section 69.1(a)(b), Rule XXIII of RA 9184;
BAC properly prepare the bidding documents, complete with accurate information and instruction to bidders; and
Management ensure that contracts entered in the name of the Municipality as the procuring entity and all documents that form part of it be in accordance with the requirements of RA 9184.
